=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class loading options**\\n\\nI’m thinking about class names that are known before building, which seems reachable. Dynamic access instrumentation might cover `loadClass`. That could be more robust, but it might make the assert branch less clear. I wonder if including `RecordingClassLoader` that delegates to the parent and records asserts would help. It seems like it might call `super.loadClass(name)`, and maybe native supports that too. There are a lot of potential factors to consider!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether a subclass can override. I wonder if JDK's ClassLoader.loadClass delegates to the parent to find the class. That seems like a good mechanism for dynamic access. For the assertion branch, should I use the context loader? It looks like using a context loader whose parent has the test class might return the class I need. That's an interesting approach! I want to make sure I'm getting this right.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Native Image behavior**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether Native Image allows the use of Class.forName(TARGET_CLASS_NAME) for a test class that doesn’t have metadata. Usually, it seems to work, but I’m not completely sure. It looks like, in Native Image, Class.forName needs configuration if it can’t be determined statically. Here, if the string is static final and initialized from a class literal, Native Image might recognize it as a constant. It’s interesting to think how these elements play together!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Improving integration coverage**\\n\\nI need to focus on the remaining call sites while ensuring they're properly scoped. When considering \\\"high-coverage integration,\\\" I want to ensure that the public methods of the Descriptor are added, but I don't want the dedicated file to be too large. I could include methods like getParams to resol